Argo workflows and why not Airflow?

Neng Liangpornrattana
Dec 23 · 6 min read

Now with the project that I work with Use the workflow manager tool called Argo workflows (hereinafter referred to as Argo enough) as a workflow control tool for the data pipeline. When team members know that choosing this tool, there is a question as to why? ? Because at first we used a tool called Apache Airflow (which is now referred to as Airflow enough). Why not choose to use it again?

This post is trying to show how Argo works. Why did you choose this tool compared to Airflow?

Start !!

Is data engineering work. In fact, there are a lot of steps to calculate But if only the main There are not many. And most importantly, it has a pattern of the process and this pattern will be repeated, like every night, which calculates the steps that are clearly defined We can call it workflow.

In wikipedia, it's defined as workflow.

A workflow consists of an orchestrated and repeatable pattern of activity

It is also a good explanation of workflow.

Flow

We already know that work has flow from one place to another. But how does it flow ???
Imagine a river It will flow from the upstream to downstream. In the middle of it there might be a separate river. Or there may be rivers from other streams converging

The above image is an example of a workflow. The flow model would be Split into two lines, as a branch of your own, or have merge into another branch or from many lines into a single branch

So how do we assign each unit to behave in the manner that we want it to be ??

DAG

From the question above, can be answered by implementing our flow with the concept of DAG. DAG is very condensed.

  • Directed - Direction
  • Acyclic - Do not go back to the original point.
  • Graph - Connection

From the above qualifications Will find that it is the behavior of flow

HOW?

We want to create a workflow and how to create ?? Right now there are many tools that allow us to implement workflows such as

  • Oozie - the one that came with Hadoop. So write DAG with XML.
  • Luigi - Created by Spotify. Write DAG with Python.
  • Azkaban - Created by Linkedin. Write DAG with YAML.
  • Airflow - Created by Airbnb. Write DAG with Python.

Why not Airflow?

As mentioned above, there are actually tasks that we deploy on Airflow, but we have 3 main limitations:

  • Time - Time restrictions When boarding for production, it is necessary to use an efficient server and therefore require longer provisioning time.
  • Infrastructure - No need for more tools because Airflow needs at least 2 state management tools, Redis and MySQL.
  • Maintainability - The biggest reason is that we don't have many people to watch and all the tools.

Why Argo?

So why Argo can solve the problem

  • Container-native for Kubernetes

Is that this project is designed to be The container-base already exists and is already running on Kubernetes. This means that we don't need any new machines or machines. Just install the Argo Controller on the Cluster of this service and you're ready to go. No need for additional tools

The engineer who takes care of it does not have to learn anything new. If he doesn't say Argo belongs, then he doesn't have to pay attention. Finally, every unit is a familiar Kubernetes resource.

Only this factor can solve all three problems that are straight away.

How Argo works?

Argo only works with a single controller installed. That's it. Then the client side just triggers the command.

> argo submit task.yaml

Start working as described in the file named task.yaml.

The contents of the task.yaml will then be saved to etcd which is a storage for Kubernetes that has an Argo controller. If it comes, the controller will work as announced in task.yaml.

In this file, task.yaml will be in YAML format, what is inside this file This is a resource declaration that allows Kubernetes to understand what to do with the steps. This resource is called a Custom Resource Definition or CRD. This resource is declared as a custom workflow type. The person reading it is the Argo controller.

The look of task.yaml will look like this

The components of this CRD will be declared as

  • Workflow type
  • generateName to name the workflow, but the generateName has one property: it generates a random random key, causing the workflow name to be unique each time it is created.
  • Tell the start point to go to the entry point called the whalesay
  • In templates, the working unit templates are announced. Or simply compare it to a function that can accept an argument. One unit is bound to one docker image. Once called, it creates a docker container from the declared image and works as we wrote. In image

After the controller reads this CRD, it will start working as announced by creating 1 pod per 1 step. Once the work is done, it will update to etcd and the controller will continue to operate in the next step.

This is simple, not complicated.

How to define DAG?

DAG determines what to do in each step. Suppose we want to do something more, for example

  • step A start working
  • step B and C will start working after step A is completed
  • step D will start working after step B and step C work is completed.

We will define in our task.yaml about this

Will use dependencies to determine what to do first and foremost

Resubmit

It must be when our flow does not work. Argo has prepared a command named resubmit.

> argo resubmit --memoized hello-world-5randomletters

The workflow name that has been generated must be entered when submit. It will clone the completed step and start executing the failed step. Do not be afraid that the step will be repeated for sure

Artifacts

There are cases where we need to send a state from one step to another.
Argo has something called Artifacts, which is simply called Object storage. It has S3 S3 compatibility, which is just any storage. Can talk through the S3 protocol, such as the S3 itself or MinIO

When defining DAG, simply specify which path artifact to use as the output of the first step and which path to be input to the next step. See the link below.

argoproj / argo

You can't perform that action at this time. You signed in with another tab or window. You signed out in another tab or ...

github.com

What about scheduling?

Without a scheduler, this is probably not a full-time workflow manager. But .........

The funny thing about Argo is that it doesn't exist.

But it happened to me that I found this thread that discussed He explains like The development team won't make a Scheduler in Argo. It's a duplicate of CronJob in Kubernetes. Why, if you want to use Kubernetes, then that's all. There are no examples. I am dogmatic.

The principle is simple. The CronJob that we define is triggered to create a docker container that we define. Our docker image should have two things: Argo's instruction set and our DAG definition file, if necessary. Another configuration can be copied to the image in the Dockerfile.

In my cron it looks like this

In the key image will be the image that we have built. I have punctured the entrypoint in the image to receive params so we can decide which workflow to submit.

Integration & Deployment

This is the topic that I spent the most time on it. Because each device will naturally use different tools The posture of the body is not the same. This project uses Jenkins as the bow for integration and deployment.

After pushing the necessary code into the git repository, which I intended to be mono-repo, this repository will have the source code of many pipelines.

On the Jenkins page there is an option to choose which pipeline to build because you want to separate each build version for each pipeline. If having to rollback, you don't have to worry about interfering with other pipelines.

Build step will start at

  • checkout code first
  • build docker image set for Argo cli with DAG definition files
  • build a docker image set for the operation unit defined in DAG in templates
  • push 2 images above to the docker registry
  • Apply apply to the K8S CronJob resource in order to be modified according to the chosen pipeline first.
  • Then wait for it to trigger the CronJob

Monitoring

After our workflow is done We can see the work by Argo has provided a web ui as well.

Which the UI will summarize according to the step that has been process and details for each flow and each step

Another feature that can be done is the Exit handler. After working until the end of the flow, whether completed or not completed, it will always enter the Exit handler.

As an example, it will go to send-email first to send mail, then check what status is. If Succeeded, it will do. If not Succeeded, it will do again as defined in the templates block.

Argo VS Airflow

Argo and Airflow advantages

Both tools Able to work as intended There may be some easy, some difficult But can finish the job. There is also a Live UI that can display and can see the status of the workflow, including Logging. In addition, can set the timeout time and how many retry.

Argo Advantages

Centralized logging can be very easy as deploy on Kubernetes which has already been implemented But it's not fair to Airflow because if you use Airflow to deploy on this cluster, you can do it too. But coincidentally, the context in which we are comparing cannot be deployed on the cluster.

Another thing is Working unit is container-base Therefore can use any tools or languages ​​to create this unit of work

Airflow Advantages

The Airflow Web UI is the most impressive. There is a DAG summary and the best after trying Argo and found that we can operate anything through the Web UI. Argo has to do it through CLI only.

Disadvantages of Argo and Airflow

Both tools are difficult to deploy, but they are different. For example, for Airflow, every time you deploy the DAG definition file to the worker machine, because the worker needs to know what steps to take from the DAG file. Python definition, which can be done but is more complicated. And there are other issues, but overall, deployment is still difficult

While Argo doesn't have to worry about deploying DAG definition files to worker machines, Kubernetes's mechanism handles this. But it turns out that the headache is more about how to build a docker image and because it's still new So there is still no practice that should be followed Have to come to trial and error together for a long time

Disadvantages Argo

The Argo concept is not difficult at all. But it's difficult to deploy on Kubernetes. Because I have to understand many things about Kubernetes first, including its new stuff. There are still many bugs. There must be a temporary workaround to put in a lot. Still not that much. And as I mentioned in the UI, we are not able to operate anything on the Argo UI.

Disadvantages Airflow

Meaning only use Python

conclude

Argo himself was able to solve problems in the context of the project I was working on. Airflow was not bad in terms of functionality, but just the deployment doesn't fit into this context. In actual work, it's not dedicate that this project will only use Argo.
